Title:
TinyLoad v7.1

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
TinyLoad is a Windows x64 PE packer/crypter that wraps an input executable into a self-extracting stub and runs the decrypted payload directly in memory (no original payload written back to disk). It aims to hinder reverse engineering and static analysis by layering optional protections: custom LZ77 compression, a custom virtual-machine (VM) based encryption scheme, and on-demand page decryption via vectored exception handling (VEH). Each build mutates by randomizing VM opcode placement into multiple independently keyed subtables, making packed outputs non-identical across runs. It also includes anti-dump measures by redirecting key WinAPI calls through stub wrappers and zeroing the payload’s import directory after load to complicate import reconstruction from memory dumps. The project is a single C++ file with no external dependencies and is built with MinGW. It’s primarily useful for red team tooling developers, malware analysts/researchers (for understanding packer tradecraft), and defenders building unpacking/detection logic.

Technical Focus:
- PE packing/crypter stub design (append payload, in-memory execution)
- Custom LZ77 compression (hash-chain matching, 64KB window)
- VM-based obfuscation/encryption (opcode virtualization, subtable randomization)
- Vectored Exception Handler (VEH) page-fault driven on-demand decryption (PAGE_NOACCESS)
- Anti-dump techniques (IAT/import directory destruction, API wrapper indirection)
- Windows memory protections and page-level re-encryption watchdog logic

Use Cases:
- Packing internal red-team payloads/tools to test detection and unpacking pipelines
- Studying VM-based packer design and mutation strategies for RE practice
- Developing defensive heuristics/signatures for packers using VEH page-fault decryption
- Evaluating memory-dump resistance techniques (import wiping, partial in-memory plaintext)

Keywords:
TinyLoad, PE packer, crypter, Windows x64, in-memory execution, stub loader, LZ77, hash chain, virtual machine obfuscation, VM interpreter, opcode randomization, stream cipher, ROTL, ROTR, VEH, VectoredExceptionHandler, PAGE_NOACCESS, page-fault decryption, VirtualAlloc, GetProcAddress, import directory wiping, anti-dump, memory dumping, PE sections